The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                        NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 New Delhi, Oct. 22: The new IITs which are struggling to get teachers have been given permission to offer a higher salary to faculty than that fixed by the government provided they can pay for it with their own money.          
	The decision was taken at a meeting yesterday between HRD minister Kapil Sibal and directors of eight IITs set up in the past two years, a ministry official said. The directors raised the problems they were facing in hiring teachers.                  
	 Calcutta: Mamata Banerjee will hit the citys streets tomorrow as planned to demand the withdrawal of joint forces and closure of armed CPM camps from Maoist-affected Purulia, Bankura and West Midnapore. The Trinamul chief will lead a padayatra from Bidhan Nagar station to the Beliaghata house.                   
	 Patna: Five policemen were killed and one was injured in a landmine blast triggered by Maoists in Sheohar district, 125km northeast of Patna, on Friday night. Sheohar goes to polls on Sunday                  
	 Midnapore: Suspected Maoist Foren Singh Sardar, wanted in at least 21 cases including nine murders, has been arrested in Poradiha on the West Midnapore- Bankura border. A one-shotter, ammunition, two detonators and some explosives have been seized from him.                                                                                                                                              
